<taxonomicName id="C3074ABD8D36450DC843ED07CDD0C51C" authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Katatopygia</taxonomicName>
gen. n. A Male terminaliaof 
<taxonomicName id="61C8C2FFC3BD2434BBC7C9B9F297E59E" authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia erythropyga" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erythropyga">Katatopygia erythropyga</taxonomicName>
(Holmgren, 1883), dorsal view, T9 removed B Aedagus and parameres of 
<taxonomicName id="B0FC15354ECCCBC49ED842A874D99D46" authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia erythropyga" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erythropyga">Katatopygia erythropyga</taxonomicName>
(Holmgren, 1883), lateral view. Abbreviations: aed = aedeagus; aed ap= aedeagal apodeme; ap pro = apical processus of gonostylus; ej ap =ejaculatory apodeme; gc II = section II of gonocoxite; gc III = section III of gonocoxite; gc ap = gonocoxal apodeme; gst = gonostylus; hyp lb = hypandrial lobe; par = paramere; par ap = parameral apodeme; vas def = vas deferens.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="9E3E0655E69ECA80CFB9B6FEC26DBB06" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">
Female terminalia (Fig. 7
<normalizedToken id="595AB5468106ED1D54EF5DB1B592DFB2" originalValue="A–F">A-F</normalizedToken>
). Tergite VIII well developed, subrectangular. Sternite VIII well developed, entirely fused with gonocoxite VIII that is tapered and bearing several strong setae at apical margin. Tergite IX well developed, shorter than Tergite VIII. Gonapophysis VIII hyaline, indistinct. Gonapophysis IX ventrally divided and retracted into segment VIII, in some species projected into a pointed apex, while in other short and blunt. Tergite X very short, laterally fused with sternite X that is completely divided ventrally and projected caudally. Cerci one-segmented, ovate.
</paragraph>
<caption id="9D6A3E0D8E8324002FFCC104830A497F" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">
<paragraph id="D75BADEA33E37618D31791A69AC14576" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">
