<paragraph id="9C75E34BFC022E4324909DDDB93B848E" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">Larvae unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F14A2D5DBEFA6965A80FF056AEBCF431" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" type="notes on biology">
<paragraph id="33546A2751CD281985153D4F5CA69E70" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">Notes on biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="91BCEE4380B68722E34FE9EC011BEF9D" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">
The Nordic species are most abundant in boreal Taiga and subarctic environments, and are possibly strictly boreal-montane. The adults, at least of 
<taxonomicName id="780BEFDD461EFA291AE10DE6DA7650B4" authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia sahlbergi" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahlbergi">Katatopygia sahlbergi</taxonomicName>
, seem to be attracted by light, which could suggest nocturnal activity. Larval habitats are unknown for all species in the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0772CF9BD49FA77A768121DDEDCC951C" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="A2FBAF9D6F3F5F06F3042A43AE1A9A38" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="33B3058F04DDA9CB4163ABD3193535D5" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">
A mainly Holarctic genus with the exception of 
<taxonomicName id="09C914CEC3D4AE809033F6A31F63D065" authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia laticauda" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laticauda">Katatopygia laticauda</taxonomicName>
(Saigusa, 1968), comb. n. described from Taiwan in the Oriental Region (
<bibRefCitation id="7F9F7DA01AD4E89FE18E94CC6AA9480D" author="Saigusa, T" journalOrPublisher="Sieboldia" pageId="16" pageNumber="53" pagination="1 - 24" title="The genus Boletina Staeger from Taiwan (Diptera Mycetophilidae)." volume="4" year="1968">Saigusa 1968</bibRefCitation>
). The greatest diversity is found in Western North America and in the Eastern Palaearctic with four species in each of the regions (Table 1).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3CB4E86DBE8EEC0F275E99BDAD5F98E" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="6F18449A76B7C546F8A14E5F4B300BFB" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB6D28067EF57A63BBCC39CD76EF5C47" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">
<taxonomicName id="F0B17190F40C0870CF6C3EED1151A5A6" authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Katatopygia</taxonomicName>
is derived from the Greek words katatonis, meaning &quot;broader than high&quot;, pygo-, meaning 
<normalizedToken id="72BA8BFFC71D2A2552DADAA0991CDE69" originalValue="“rump”">&quot;rump&quot;</normalizedToken>
or 
<normalizedToken id="91E067FD2FE320E5942911919F328FAB" originalValue="“buttock”">&quot;buttock&quot;</normalizedToken>
and the suffix -ia denoting pertaining to. The name refers to the characteristic broad and dorsoventrally flattened terminalia shared by all males in the genus. The name is a noun and is feminine.
</paragraph>
<subSection id="1CA0A633FEF1BB95F1E0F0A76673C3BF" pageId="5" pageNumber="42" type="the species of katatopygia">
<paragraph id="EA9315D51B3897C8D617F6DE19DC2BBB" pageId="5" pageNumber="42">
